Here are both approaches in .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — simple string vs. full object**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs
[RelayCommand]
async Task GoToDetails(Product product)
{
    // Approach A: pass just the ID as a query string
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");

    // Approach B: pass the full object via dictionary
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        ["product"] = product
    });
}
```

**3. Receive on the target ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`**
```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty] string productId;
    [ObservableProperty] Product product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: simple string param arrives as string
        if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var id))
            ProductId = id.ToString();

        // Approach B: complex object arrives as-is (no serialization)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
            Product = p;
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String query param | Dictionary object |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `$"route?key={val}"` | `GoToAsync(route, dict)` |
| **Type in handler** | `string` | Original object type |
| **Survives serialization** | Yes (URL-safe) | No (in-memory only) |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, small values | Complex/nested objects |

The `IDictionary<string, object>` overload of `GoToAsync` keeps object references in memory, so no serialization occurs — your `Product` arrives as the exact same instance.
